    "text": "4.4 RQ2. Ablation Study In this section, we evaluate the effectiveness of the key components of CaVulner . During the vulnerable code identification stage of CaVulner_diff , we remove the coarse-grained vulnerable methods localization and fine-grained vulnerable code blocks identification based on multi-source information fusion. Instead, we let the LLM identify the vulnerable code based on the fix commit diff files and CVE information. In the VIC tracing phase, we use the same approach as CaVulner . In CaVulner_ast , after identifying the vulnerable code blocks, we replace the use of LLM for tracing the VICs with an AST-based line mapping approach. As shown in Table 4 , at the CVE level, CaVulner_diff achieves only 49.43% accuracy, indicating that without Coarse-grained Vulnerable Method Localization and Fine-grained Vulnerable Code Block Identification the LLM often misidentifies vulnerable versions. Introducing AST - based tracing raises CVE accuracy to 65.91%. Finally, the full CaVulner reaches 73.30%, outperforming CaVulner_diff and CaVulner_ast . To validate the effectiveness of our LLM-based VIC tracing module, we further compare its performance against the AST-based baseline ( CaVulner_ast ) using the strict CVE-level accuracy metric. As shown in Table 4 , the AST-based approach achieves a CVE accuracy of 65.91%. Since CVE-level accuracy requires an exact match of the entire vulnerable version range, any deviation in identifying the VIC results in a failure for that CVE. By replacing the AST algorithm with our LLM-based semantic tracing, CaVulner significantly improves the accuracy to 73.30%. This absolute gain of 7.39% demonstrates that the LLM-based approach is superior in correctly pinpointing the exact VIC. Unlike the AST method, which may be disrupted by complex code refactorings and fail to identify the true origin, the LLM’s semantic understanding enables CaVulner to correctly determine the start of the vulnerability lifecycle in substantially more cases, thereby securing the correctness of the final version sets. At the version level, CaVulner_diff achieves a high precision (94.11%) but suffers from poor recall (58.12%) and a moderate F1 - score (71.86%). CaVulner_ast improves substantially on recall (80.23%) and F1-score (88.72%) and achieves high precision (99.22%). However, both its recall and F1 - score remain lower than those of CaVulner . This demonstrates that although AST - based tracing can boost precision, integrating LLM - driven VIC tracing is essential to maximize recall and overall F1 performance. We further evaluated three additional LLMs, including DeepSeek R1, GPT 4.1-mini, and Qwen turbo. Table 5 compares the performance of four different large language models on both CVE and version levels, all run with zero temperature to ensure determinism.",
